@speaker2: "...but then the upside of the leverage mechanism is also competed away...if something is good then many people realize it and that's going to be competition... if you start a company that is only leveraging the fact that it's software doesn't leverage other technologies then it's probably much harder to succeed now compared to 20 years ago...what i'm trying to get at is when this leverage mechanism is just became possible because of some technology, much larger values and returns are possible then and then it's going to be competed away. so i think it's very important to think about what are the new leverage mechanisms that are becoming available."
(introducing the challenge:  leverage mechanisms create advantages which are eventually competed away.)

@speaker2: "...so obviously i'm going to argue that ai is the relatively new one that is coming into the picture and it's slowly expanding its scope and reach...to from an individual level to groups of people and to the point where it can benefit humanity as a whole...let's maybe start looking at this at an individual level...i personally use ai for me is in education context...i think i spent a lot of time, especially weekends, learning about new concepts...asking... now i think talking about this even hours and just learning about new things..."
(transitioning to the core discussion about ai as a new leverage mechanism, starting with the impact on individuals)

@speaker2: "...if you think about leverage, when i think about ai as a leverage, this learning, what is an input and output, the input is my time and effort to understand some concept that i don't understand and the output is the conceptual understanding happening in my brain and maybe also some knowledge...with ai this given input results in larger output...let's say if i'm trying to learn some specific things about a distributed system...then before this kind of a generative ai i would have to google this and then probably a wikipedia page, which is typically not beginner friendly...now because ai can contextualize everything i know and generate dynamically just the right amount of materials at the right difficulty, i can much learn much easier."
(demonstrates ai's benefits in his own life. provides a clear example of ai's leverage effect by comparing pre and post ai experience.  sounds enthusiastic and confident 🟡)

@speaker2:  "...i think that's the big lesson from the learning...what i'm saying is the barrier to learn new area is like collapsing essentially...this is good, and you probably heard about this a lot, but is this good everywhere?...i think there's some we have to be careful and have a comprehensive look...when everything is easier to learn, people are learning everything, then there is an opportunity cost of not learning is getting higher..."
(a shift to the potential downsides and wider implications of easy access to knowledge.  a shift from excitement 🟡 to slight concern 🟠)

@speaker2: "...as an extreme example if you don't use ai, you just don't think about it at all, and you just do your thing, you're not lazy just doing your own thing and everyone else is just learning new things and getting better and so on then you're kind of behind in society. that's the opportunity cost...but just because its relatively decided what the valuable skill is, that's what's happening...yeah i think the in society the valuable skill is determined based on the supply and demand of what is scarce...as opposed to an objective value it provides..."
(illustrates this opportunity cost with an example, and highlights the shift from objective value to scarcity as a driver of skill valuation.)

@speaker2: "...i think one extreme example is human vision...it's from objective perspective this is extremely complicated and advanced feature...but this incredible capability is so abundant that it's having that doesn't help you excelling in modern society...scarcity is a very important necessary condition for any highly valuable skill...what are some great skills or opportunities to have...whatever evolution did not teach equip us then that's kind of a good starting point because if it did then everyone has it built into dna and that's probably not that scarce..."
(introduces the concept of scarcity and how it relates to valuable skills.  this section demonstrates in-depth knowledge and thinking.)

@speaker2: "...that's kind of the some implications of learning getting easier...and so the acquisition of the new knowledge gets cheap the scarcest factor is the motivation to explore and curiosity is kind of the characteristics that probably will be more important...well i mean it has been always important but i think it's getting more and more because the learning cost is going down but not zero...learning a new concept is not something that i would say everyone finds pleasing because you feel challenged and this cognitive challenge is not comfortable...and so to overcome that curiosity can be i know there's a pain but i need to get this because i'm so curious about it...if you're not curious i think there's a way to have a correction mechanism...which is okay i'm going to go through this short-term pain but there will be a long-term reward...if you build in enough of this reward something can get over it...more broadly technology changes what is scarce...just being aware of such changes even if you're not directly contributing to it is very important."
